{"index_version": 2, "scope": "llm-wiki", "vault": "/sessions/laughing-awesome-turing/mnt/workspace/projekt/skills/auto-graph-wiki/examples/llm-wiki", "indexed_at": "2026-04-27T22:52:19.406111", "pages": [{"id": "index.md", "scope": "llm-wiki", "title": "Example LLM-Wiki — Index", "path_parts": [], "path_no_ext": "index", "breadcrumb": "Example LLM-Wiki — Index", "metadata": {}, "chunks": [{"heading": "Example LLM-Wiki — Index", "text": "> An example wiki demonstrating how `auto-graph-wiki` works. Replace this with your own wiki content.\n> Pages live under `pages/`, each with frontmatter that the indexer reads.\n> Run `python ../../scripts/reindex.py` to build the search index.\n\nThis wiki contains four example pages across two domains: `cooking` and `productivity`. They are intentionally generic — the goal is to show what frontmatter looks like and how it powers cheap retrieval, not to teach any particular subject.", "tf": {"example": 4, "llm-wiki": 2, "index": 3, "wiki": 3, "demonstrating": 1, "how": 2, "auto-graph-wiki": 1, "works": 1, "replace": 1, "your": 1, "own": 1, "content": 1, "pages": 3, "live": 1, "under": 1, "each": 1, "frontmatter": 2, "indexer": 1, "reads": 1, "run": 1, "python": 1, "scripts": 1, "reindex": 1, "py": 1, "build": 1, "search": 1, "contains": 1, "four": 1, "across": 1, "domains": 1, "cooking": 1, "productivity": 1, "intentionally": 1, "generic": 1, "goal": 1, "show": 1, "what": 1, "looks": 1, "like": 1, "it": 1, "powers": 1, "cheap": 1, "retrieval": 1, "teach": 1, "particular": 1, "subject": 1}, "norm": 30.876303003243713}], "wiki_links": [], "tags": [], "mtime": 1777320381.8819757}, {"id": "pages/cooking/knead-techniques.md", "scope": "llm-wiki", "title": "Kneading Techniques", "path_parts": ["pages", "cooking"], "path_no_ext": "pages/cooking/knead-techniques", "breadcrumb": "cooking › Kneading Techniques", "metadata": {"domain": "cooking", "description": "Methods for developing gluten in bread dough without overworking", "summary": "Modern bread baking uses gentle stretch-and-fold techniques rather than vigorous kneading. Time replaces force.", "keywords": ["kneading", "stretch-and-fold", "gluten", "bread", "technique"], "aliases": ["gluten development", "no-knead bread"], "related": ["sourdough-basics"], "updated": "2026-02-03"}, "chunks": [{"heading": "Kneading Techniques", "text": "Traditional kneading was about brute mechanical force — work the dough until it's smooth. Modern home baking has shifted toward gentler methods because they suit higher-hydration doughs better.", "tf": {"kneading": 3, "techniques": 2, "traditional": 1, "about": 1, "brute": 1, "mechanical": 1, "force": 1, "work": 1, "dough": 1, "until": 1, "it": 1, "smooth": 1, "modern": 1, "home": 1, "baking": 1, "shifted": 1, "toward": 1, "gentler": 1, "methods": 1, "because": 1, "suit": 1, "higher-hydration": 1, "doughs": 1, "better": 1}, "norm": 18.9276043449378}, {"heading": "Stretch and fold", "text": "Every 30 minutes during bulk ferment, lift one edge of the dough, stretch it up, and fold it over. Rotate the bowl, repeat for all four sides. Three to four sets is typical.", "tf": {"stretch": 3, "fold": 3, "every": 1, "minutes": 1, "during": 1, "bulk": 1, "ferment": 1, "lift": 1, "edge": 1, "dough": 1, "it": 2, "up": 1, "over": 1, "rotate": 1, "bowl": 1, "repeat": 1, "four": 2, "sides": 1, "three": 1, "sets": 1, "typical": 1}, "norm": 18.215641634073886}, {"heading": "Slap and fold (Bertinet)", "text": "For very wet doughs, use the slap-and-fold method: pick up the dough, slap it on the counter, fold it back on itself, repeat. Builds gluten in 5–10 minutes without flour on the counter.", "tf": {"slap": 3, "fold": 3, "bertinet": 2, "very": 1, "wet": 1, "doughs": 1, "use": 1, "slap-and-fold": 1, "method": 1, "pick": 1, "up": 1, "dough": 1, "it": 2, "counter": 2, "back": 1, "itself": 1, "repeat": 1, "builds": 1, "gluten": 1, "minutes": 1, "without": 1, "flour": 1}, "norm": 20.222671873859607}, {"heading": "When to stop", "text": "Test for gluten development with the windowpane test — stretch a small piece thin enough to see light through. If it tears immediately, more time or another fold is needed.", "tf": {"when": 2, "stop": 2, "test": 2, "gluten": 1, "development": 1, "windowpane": 1, "stretch": 1, "small": 1, "piece": 1, "thin": 1, "enough": 1, "see": 1, "light": 1, "through": 1, "it": 1, "tears": 1, "immediately": 1, "more": 1, "time": 1, "another": 1, "fold": 1, "needed": 1}, "norm": 17.587329861738255}], "wiki_links": [], "tags": [], "mtime": 1777247281.4471471}, {"id": "pages/cooking/sourdough-basics.md", "scope": "llm-wiki", "title": "Sourdough Basics", "path_parts": ["pages", "cooking"], "path_no_ext": "pages/cooking/sourdough-basics", "breadcrumb": "cooking › Sourdough Basics", "metadata": {"domain": "cooking", "description": "Foundations of sourdough — starter, hydration, fermentation timing", "summary": "Sourdough is leavened by wild yeast and lactobacilli kept alive in a flour-and-water starter. Three variables dominate outcomes — hydration ratio, fermentation time, and dough temperature.", "keywords": ["sourdough", "starter", "hydration", "fermentation", "bread", "baking"], "aliases": ["wild-yeast bread", "levain bread"], "related": ["knead-techniques", "oven-spring"], "updated": "2026-01-15"}, "chunks": [{"heading": "Sourdough Basics", "text": "Sourdough is the oldest form of leavened bread — yeast and lactobacilli capture themselves out of the air and live in a starter culture you keep going indefinitely.", "tf": {"sourdough": 3, "basics": 2, "oldest": 1, "form": 1, "leavened": 1, "bread": 1, "yeast": 1, "lactobacilli": 1, "capture": 1, "themselves": 1, "out": 1, "air": 1, "live": 1, "starter": 1, "culture": 1, "keep": 1, "going": 1, "indefinitely": 1}, "norm": 17.4493738257771}, {"heading": "Starter", "text": "A starter is flour and water in roughly 1:1 ratio by weight. Feed daily at room temperature, or weekly if refrigerated. A healthy starter doubles within 4–8 hours of feeding.", "tf": {"starter": 4, "flour": 1, "water": 1, "roughly": 1, "ratio": 1, "weight": 1, "feed": 1, "daily": 1, "room": 1, "temperature": 1, "weekly": 1, "refrigerated": 1, "healthy": 1, "doubles": 1, "within": 1, "hours": 1, "feeding": 1}, "norm": 16.43886917979823}, {"heading": "Hydration", "text": "Hydration is the ratio of water to flour, expressed as a percentage. 65% is firm and easy to handle; 80% is wet and produces an open crumb. Beginners usually start at 70%.", "tf": {"hydration": 3, "ratio": 1, "water": 1, "flour": 1, "expressed": 1, "percentage": 1, "firm": 1, "easy": 1, "handle": 1, "wet": 1, "produces": 1, "open": 1, "crumb": 1, "beginners": 1, "usually": 1, "start": 1}, "norm": 15.73584064100207}, {"heading": "Fermentation", "text": "Fermentation has two phases: bulk ferment (4–6h at 24°C) and final proof (1–2h, or overnight in the fridge). Cold proofing develops flavour and makes scoring easier.", "tf": {"fermentation": 3, "phases": 1, "bulk": 1, "ferment": 1, "final": 1, "proof": 1, "overnight": 1, "fridge": 1, "cold": 1, "proofing": 1, "develops": 1, "flavour": 1, "makes": 1, "scoring": 1, "easier": 1}, "norm": 15.496870734888764}, {"heading": "Common mistakes", "text": "Most failures trace back to three causes: starter not active enough, dough underproofed, oven too cold. Diagnose by tracking volume change during bulk ferment.", "tf": {"common": 2, "mistakes": 2, "most": 1, "failures": 1, "trace": 1, "back": 1, "three": 1, "causes": 1, "starter": 1, "active": 1, "enough": 1, "dough": 1, "underproofed": 1, "oven": 1, "too": 1, "cold": 1, "diagnose": 1, "tracking": 1, "volume": 1, "change": 1, "during": 1, "bulk": 1, "ferment": 1}, "norm": 16.657770282806244}], "wiki_links": [], "tags": [], "mtime": 1777247271.6379967}, {"id": "pages/productivity/daily-review.md", "scope": "llm-wiki", "title": "Daily Review", "path_parts": ["pages", "productivity"], "path_no_ext": "pages/productivity/daily-review", "breadcrumb": "productivity › Daily Review", "metadata": {"domain": "productivity", "description": "A short end-of-day ritual that catches loose ends before they become urgent", "summary": "A 10-minute review at the end of each day surfaces unfinished work, captures next steps, and resets focus for tomorrow. Three questions structure it: what moved, what stalled, what comes next.", "keywords": ["daily review", "ritual", "GTD", "end of day", "planning"], "aliases": ["evening review", "EOD review"], "related": ["note-taking-systems"], "updated": "2026-03-12"}, "chunks": [{"heading": "Daily Review", "text": "A daily review is not a journal entry. It is an *audit* — a quick pass over the day's work to make sure nothing important was lost.", "tf": {"daily": 3, "review": 3, "journal": 1, "entry": 1, "it": 1, "audit": 1, "quick": 1, "pass": 1, "over": 1, "day": 1, "work": 1, "make": 1, "sure": 1, "nothing": 1, "important": 1, "lost": 1}, "norm": 16.267421651726774}, {"heading": "Structure", "text": "Three questions, two minutes each:\n\n- **What moved?** Tasks completed, decisions made, conversations that mattered.\n- **What stalled?** Anything blocked, delayed, or quietly slipping. Note the cause.\n- **What comes next?** The single most important thing for tomorrow morning.", "tf": {"structure": 2, "three": 1, "questions": 1, "minutes": 1, "each": 1, "what": 3, "moved": 1, "tasks": 1, "completed": 1, "decisions": 1, "made": 1, "conversations": 1, "mattered": 1, "stalled": 1, "anything": 1, "blocked": 1, "delayed": 1, "quietly": 1, "slipping": 1, "note": 1, "cause": 1, "comes": 1, "next": 1, "single": 1, "most": 1, "important": 1, "thing": 1, "tomorrow": 1, "morning": 1}, "norm": 18.838681039067385}, {"heading": "Capture loop", "text": "Anything unfinished at end of day either gets a deliberate \"later\" disposition (scheduled, deferred, archived) or gets pushed to tomorrow's top of list. Nothing remains in ambiguous limbo.", "tf": {"capture": 2, "loop": 2, "anything": 1, "unfinished": 1, "end": 1, "day": 1, "either": 1, "gets": 2, "deliberate": 1, "later": 1, "disposition": 1, "scheduled": 1, "deferred": 1, "archived": 1, "pushed": 1, "tomorrow": 1, "top": 1, "list": 1, "nothing": 1, "remains": 1, "ambiguous": 1, "limbo": 1}, "norm": 17.527503837046517}, {"heading": "Cadence", "text": "Done daily, the review is light — 5–10 minutes. Skipped for a week, it accumulates into something harder. The discipline is consistency, not depth.", "tf": {"cadence": 2, "done": 1, "daily": 1, "review": 1, "light": 1, "minutes": 1, "skipped": 1, "week": 1, "it": 1, "accumulates": 1, "into": 1, "something": 1, "harder": 1, "discipline": 1, "consistency": 1, "depth": 1}, "norm": 13.596171480824312}], "wiki_links": [], "tags": [], "mtime": 1777247348.6310055}, {"id": "pages/productivity/note-taking-systems.md", "scope": "llm-wiki", "title": "Note-Taking Systems", "path_parts": ["pages", "productivity"], "path_no_ext": "pages/productivity/note-taking-systems", "breadcrumb": "productivity › Note-Taking Systems", "metadata": {"domain": "productivity", "description": "Comparison of common personal knowledge management approaches", "summary": "Three systems dominate personal knowledge management: Zettelkasten (atomic notes with bidirectional links), PARA (project-driven folders), and Building a Second Brain (capture-organize-distill-express). Each suits different mental models.", "keywords": ["zettelkasten", "PARA", "second brain", "PKM", "notes", "knowledge management"], "aliases": ["PKM", "knowledge management", "note systems"], "related": ["daily-review", "capture-workflow"], "updated": "2026-03-10"}, "chunks": [{"heading": "Note-Taking Systems", "text": "A note-taking system is not a tool — it is a *contract* with your future self about how you will retrieve information you have written down. Three contracts dominate the field.", "tf": {"note-taking": 3, "systems": 2, "system": 1, "tool": 1, "it": 1, "contract": 1, "your": 1, "future": 1, "self": 1, "about": 1, "how": 1, "retrieve": 1, "information": 1, "written": 1, "down": 1, "three": 1, "contracts": 1, "dominate": 1, "field": 1}, "norm": 17.29599925218306}, {"heading": "Zettelkasten", "text": "Atomic notes (one idea each), connected by explicit links. Originally Niklas Luhmann's system on paper index cards; now most often run in Obsidian, Logseq, or Roam. Strength: emergent structure through linking. Weakness: high friction at capture.", "tf": {"zettelkasten": 2, "atomic": 1, "notes": 1, "idea": 1, "each": 1, "connected": 1, "explicit": 1, "links": 1, "originally": 1, "niklas": 1, "luhmann": 1, "system": 1, "paper": 1, "index": 1, "cards": 1, "now": 1, "most": 1, "often": 1, "run": 1, "obsidian": 1, "logseq": 1, "roam": 1, "strength": 1, "emergent": 1, "structure": 1, "through": 1, "linking": 1, "weakness": 1, "high": 1, "friction": 1, "capture": 1}, "norm": 18.095562374582787}, {"heading": "PARA", "text": "Projects, Areas, Resources, Archives. A folder hierarchy that mirrors what you are actively working on. Designed by Tiago Forte. Strength: matches how most office work is structured. Weakness: re-organizing is tedious as projects shift.", "tf": {"para": 2, "projects": 2, "areas": 1, "resources": 1, "archives": 1, "folder": 1, "hierarchy": 1, "mirrors": 1, "what": 1, "actively": 1, "working": 1, "designed": 1, "tiago": 1, "forte": 1, "strength": 1, "matches": 1, "how": 1, "most": 1, "office": 1, "work": 1, "structured": 1, "weakness": 1, "re-organizing": 1, "tedious": 1, "shift": 1}, "norm": 17.620024664772092}, {"heading": "Building a Second Brain", "text": "CODE: Capture, Organize, Distill, Express. A workflow rather than a structure. Notes flow from capture through to creative output. Strength: opinionated, practical. Weakness: assumes a particular creative-output goal.", "tf": {"building": 2, "second": 2, "brain": 2, "code": 1, "capture": 2, "organize": 1, "distill": 1, "express": 1, "workflow": 1, "rather": 1, "than": 1, "structure": 1, "notes": 1, "flow": 1, "through": 1, "creative": 1, "output": 1, "strength": 1, "opinionated": 1, "practical": 1, "weakness": 1, "assumes": 1, "particular": 1, "creative-output": 1, "goal": 1}, "norm": 18.941434906459655}, {"heading": "Choosing", "text": "Most people pick one and find it doesn't quite fit. The honest answer is to start with whichever feels lowest-friction, and let the actual texture of your work shape the system over time. The best system is the one you actually use.", "tf": {"choosing": 2, "most": 1, "people": 1, "pick": 1, "find": 1, "it": 1, "doesn": 1, "quite": 1, "fit": 1, "honest": 1, "answer": 1, "start": 1, "whichever": 1, "feels": 1, "lowest-friction": 1, "let": 1, "actual": 1, "texture": 1, "your": 1, "work": 1, "shape": 1, "system": 2, "over": 1, "time": 1, "best": 1, "actually": 1, "use": 1}, "norm": 17.492519096598983}], "wiki_links": [], "tags": [], "mtime": 1777247298.6364658}], "idf": {"example": 3.302585092994046, "llm-wiki": 3.302585092994046, "index": 2.8971199848858813, "wiki": 3.302585092994046, "demonstrating": 3.302585092994046, "how": 2.6094379124341005, "auto-graph-wiki": 3.302585092994046, "works": 3.302585092994046, "replace": 3.302585092994046, "your": 2.6094379124341005, "own": 3.302585092994046, "content": 3.302585092994046, "pages": 3.302585092994046, "live": 2.8971199848858813, "under": 3.302585092994046, "each": 2.6094379124341005, "frontmatter": 3.302585092994046, "indexer": 3.302585092994046, "reads": 3.302585092994046, "run": 2.8971199848858813, "python": 3.302585092994046, "scripts": 3.302585092994046, "reindex": 3.302585092994046, "py": 3.302585092994046, "build": 3.302585092994046, "search": 3.302585092994046, "contains": 3.302585092994046, "four": 2.8971199848858813, "across": 3.302585092994046, "domains": 3.302585092994046, "cooking": 3.302585092994046, "productivity": 3.302585092994046, "intentionally": 3.302585092994046, "generic": 3.302585092994046, "goal": 2.8971199848858813, "show": 3.302585092994046, "what": 2.6094379124341005, "looks": 3.302585092994046, "like":